She advanced a few ſteps nearer till ſhe came to an aged oak, which ſhaded a ſeat formed of turf. Higher up on the trunk of the tree ſomething glittered in the light of the moon. It was a white board with ſome inſcription, and faſtened to the tree by a gilt thong. Jeanette ſtepped up on the bench, and by the moonlight read the following lines in French:
La plainte eſt pour le fat, le bruit eſt pour le ſot;
L'honnête homme trompe s'eloigne, et ne dit mot.The fool complains, the knave makes a noiſe; but the ho • man decei • ed retires and ſays nothing.
